!!【柯林斯英汉双解大词典】

:<div>

blur /blɜː/

(blurring,blurred,blurs) 

1. N-COUNT A blur is a shape or area which you cannot see clearly because it has no distinct outline or because it is moving very fast. 模糊不清 

例： Out of the corner of my eye I saw a blur of movement on the other side of the glass. 从眼角我看见了玻璃窗另一边一个移动的模糊身影。 

2. V-T/V-I When a thing blurs or when something blurs it, you cannot see it clearly because its edges are no longer distinct. 使变模糊; 变模糊 

例： This creates a spectrum of colours at the edges of objects which blurs the image. 这在物体的边缘产生了一系列颜色，使图像变得模糊不清。 

3. blurred ADJ 模糊不清的 

例： ...blurred black and white photographs. …模糊的黑白照片。 

4. V-T If something blurs an idea or a distinction between things, that idea or distinction no longer seems clear. 使…变模糊 

例： ...her belief that scientists are trying to blur the distinction between 'how' and 'why' questions. …她认为科学家们正试图模糊“如何”与“为什么”问题之间的区别的想法。 

5. blurred ADJ 使变模糊的 

例： The line between fact and fiction is becoming blurred. 事实和虚构之间的界线正在变得模糊起来。 

6. V-T/V-I If your vision blurs , or if something blurs it, you cannot see things clearly. 使 (视力) 模糊; (视力) 变模糊 

例： Her eyes, behind her glasses, began to blur. 她戴着眼镜的眼睛开始看不清了。 

7. blurred ADJ (视觉) 模糊的 

例： ...visual disturbances like eye-strain and blurred vision. …诸如眼睛疲劳和视力模糊的视觉紊乱。

